\title{Look-elsewhere correction for Koide-type\\quark mass relations}
\author{Andrew M.~Brilliant\\
\small Applied Dynamics Research, Sapporo, Japan\\
\small \texttt{ab@ad-research.org}}
\date{April 2026}

\begin{document}
\maketitle

\begin{abstract}
The Koide combination $Q = (\sum m_i)/(\sum \sqrt{m_i})^2 = 2/3$, observed for the charged lepton pole masses to one part in $10^5$, has motivated numerous extensions to the quark sector. These extensions typically introduce degrees of freedom not present in the original lepton relation---evaluation at non-self renormalization scales, signed square roots, or selection among multiple quark triples---without a systematic accounting of how each degree of freedom inflates the false-positive rate. This note attempts such an accounting for the quark-only case.

We enumerate 12{,}960 trials over 20 quark triples, four sign assignments, and an audited list of physically interpretable evaluation scales, and apply two complementary tools: Model~A, a random-spectrum reference null with full four-loop CRunDec running on every draw, and Model~B, a local-stability diagnostic computed by parametric bootstrap around the observed FLAG/PDG central values. The two answer different questions and are reported separately; they cannot be combined into a single summary probability. Model~A's tail probabilities are relative rankings within the chosen log-uniform SM-like prior, not absolute significance levels. Model~B's tail probability is approximately a monotone function of $|Q - 2/3| / \sigma_Q$ and carries no additional evidential content beyond that ratio.

At full search freedom (12{,}960 trials, $N = 100{,}000$ retained Model~A draws under a log-uniform prior conditional on perturbative validity, implemented by rejection sampling with $\approx 67\%$ acceptance), the observed best closure sits at the centre of the Model~A null distribution (tail probability $\approx 0.50$) and within Model~B measurement-noise perturbations (tail probability $\approx 0.50$). Single-triple claims fixed in prior work have smaller Model~A baseline tail probabilities, in the range $\approx 0.003$--$0.04$: Cao $(c,b,t)$ self-scale at $\approx 0.007$, Rivero $(s,c,b)$ signed-self at $\approx 0.03$, and $(c,b,t)$ at $\mu = m_\tau$ at $\approx 0.003$ (or $\approx 0.004$--$0.016$ across hierarchy-preserving variants). These absolute values are conditional on the chosen reference class (one of several defensible choices; alternative reference classes such as Yukawa-derived or GUT-constrained spectra would constitute different audits not undertaken here). Within the chosen reference class, two characterized systematics exceed the binomial Monte Carlo standard error: a prior-class sub-systematic across log-uniform endpoint variations (Section~\ref{sec:prior-sensitivity}), and a loop-order systematic for running claims of $\approx 0.05$--$0.13$ across orders 1, 3, 4, 5 and reaching $\approx 0.5$ when 2-loop is included (the 2-loop full-search value of $\approx 0.04$ is an outlier explained by perturbative non-convergence of the observed Koide combination at 2-loop, not by any null-distribution pathology; self-scale claims are stable across all loop orders to four decimal places; 4-loop is used for all reported numbers, Section~\ref{sec:loop-order}). The Model~A values should be read as within-reference-class, within-loop-order relative rankings rather than as calibrated significance levels. Within those conditions the qualitative ranking is stable. The $(c, b, t)$ at $\mu = m_\tau$ claim was formulated by the present author on the same FLAG/PDG central values used in the audit; the audit began as a sanity check on that prior claim before being extended to the full quark-side search. The reported tail probability is therefore a multiplicity-corrected restatement of a prior author claim under the audit's chosen reference class, not an independent confirmation.

A matched-complexity knob-isolation test (Section~\ref{sec:isolation}) at equal trial counts across sign-only, running-only, and combined search pools finds that admitting non-self-scale running shifts the Model~A null-distribution median toward smaller residuals by more than trial-count multiplicity alone accounts for, consistent with a distinct contribution from scale freedom. We additionally tabulate the temporal trajectory of $|Q - 2/3|$ across consecutive FLAG/PDG releases as an independent discriminator: the original lepton Koide residual has tracked decreasing $\sigma_Q$ downward since 1981 (Koide's 1981 prediction $m_\tau = 1776.97$~MeV was confirmed within $0.04\sigma$ by the 1996 BES analysis), while the Rivero and Cao quark-side residuals have remained an order of magnitude or more larger than current $\sigma_Q$ across the past decade of measurement updates.
\end{abstract}


\section{Introduction}
\label{sec:intro}

Koide~\citep{Koide1982,Koide1983} observed that the charged lepton pole masses satisfy
\begin{equation}
Q(e, \mu, \tau) \;\equiv\; \frac{m_e + m_\mu + m_\tau}{\left(\sqrt{m_e} + \sqrt{m_\mu} + \sqrt{m_\tau}\right)^2} \;=\; \frac{2}{3}
\label{eq:koide}
\end{equation}
to a residual of $6.2 \times 10^{-6}$. Extensions of this relation to the quark sector include Rivero~\citep{Rivero2011} for $(s, c, b)$ with signed $\sqrt{m_s}$; Rodejohann and Zhang~\citep{RZ2011} surveying multiple triples; Cao~\citep{Cao2012} for $(c, b, t)$ at self-scales; and Brilliant~\citep{Brilliant2026cbt} for $(c, b, t)$ with $m_c$ evaluated at $\mu = m_\tau$.

Each such extension introduces one or more degrees of freedom relative to the original formula: which triple, which sign pattern for the square roots, which evaluation scale for each mass. The question this note addresses is the standard look-elsewhere question~\citep{GrossVitells2010}: \emph{given the degrees of freedom employed, how often would random or perturbed inputs produce a comparably tight closure?}

We test a specific enumerated search space (Section~\ref{sec:space}) under two specific null models (Section~\ref{sec:mc}); the resulting tail probabilities apply only to that audited search space. The status of the analysis is exploratory with respect to the full enumeration and confirmatory only for claims explicitly fixed in the prior literature.

\paragraph{Terminology and notation.} We report empirical tail fractions of the observed best residual against null distributions specified in Section~\ref{sec:mc}. We denote these by $T$ rather than $p$ to emphasize that they are descriptive rank quantiles---the fraction of null draws producing a residual at least as small as the observed one---rather than calibrated frequentist tail probabilities. The choice of symbol is deliberate: a frequentist $p$-value carries the inferential connotation of a calibrated probability of seeing at least as extreme a result under a fixed null hypothesis, which presupposes that the null hypothesis is the right one to be testing against. Our null models are reference classes of analyst convenience (Section~\ref{sec:model-a}); $T$ is meaningful as a rank within those classes but does not carry the standard $p$-value calibration. We do not use significance thresholds (e.g., $T < 0.05$) for inferential decisions, only as conventional ordering cuts in tables. The reported $T$ values are also not severity assessments in the sense of Mayo~\citep{Mayo1996,MayoSpanos2006}: severity is the attained power computed under an alternative hypothesis and is a distinct quantity~\citep{CousinsLectures}. The symbol $p$ is reserved in this paper for genuine frequentist $p$-values (e.g., $p_{\text{KS}}$ for a Kolmogorov-Smirnov test in Section~\ref{sec:loss-bias}) and for the standard binomial-SE formula $\sqrt{T(1-T)/N}$ applied to $T$ as a sample fraction.


\section{Search space}
\label{sec:space}

\subsection{Inputs}

$\overline{\text{MS}}$ quark masses are taken from FLAG~2024~\citep{FLAG2024} and PDG~2024~\citep{PDG2024}:

