\begin{abstract}
The Koide combination $Q = (\sum m_i)/(\sum \sqrt{m_i})^2 = 2/3$, observed for the charged lepton pole masses to one part in $10^5$, has motivated numerous extensions to the quark sector. These extensions typically introduce degrees of freedom not present in the original lepton relation---evaluation at non-self renormalization scales, signed square roots, or selection among multiple quark triples---without a systematic accounting of how each degree of freedom inflates the false-positive rate. This note attempts such an accounting for the quark-only case.

We enumerate 12{,}960 trials over 20 quark triples, four sign assignments, and an audited list of physically interpretable evaluation scales, and apply two complementary tools: Model~A, a random-spectrum reference null with full four-loop CRunDec running on every draw, and Model~B, a local-stability diagnostic computed by parametric bootstrap around the observed FLAG/PDG central values. The two answer different questions and are reported separately; they cannot be combined into a single summary probability. Model~A's tail probabilities are relative rankings within the chosen log-uniform SM-like prior, not absolute significance levels. Model~B's tail probability is approximately a monotone function of $|Q - 2/3| / \sigma_Q$ and carries no additional evidential content beyond that ratio.

At full search freedom (12{,}960 trials, $N = 100{,}000$ retained Model~A draws under a log-uniform prior conditional on perturbative validity, implemented by rejection sampling with $\approx 67\%$ acceptance), the observed best closure sits at the centre of the Model~A null distribution (tail probability $\approx 0.50$) and within Model~B measurement-noise perturbations (tail probability $\approx 0.50$). Single-triple claims fixed in prior work have smaller Model~A baseline tail probabilities, in the range $\approx 0.003$--$0.04$: Cao $(c,b,t)$ self-scale at $\approx 0.007$, Rivero $(s,c,b)$ signed-self at $\approx 0.03$, and $(c,b,t)$ at $\mu = m_\tau$ at $\approx 0.003$ (or $\approx 0.004$--$0.016$ across hierarchy-preserving variants). These absolute values are conditional on the chosen reference class (one of several defensible choices; alternative reference classes such as Yukawa-derived or GUT-constrained spectra would constitute different audits not undertaken here). Within the chosen reference class, two characterized systematics exceed the binomial Monte Carlo standard error: a prior-class sub-systematic across log-uniform endpoint variations (Section~\ref{sec:prior-sensitivity}), and a loop-order systematic for running claims of $\approx 0.05$--$0.13$ across orders 1, 3, 4, 5 and reaching $\approx 0.5$ when 2-loop is included (the 2-loop full-search value of $\approx 0.04$ is an outlier explained by perturbative non-convergence of the observed Koide combination at 2-loop, not by any null-distribution pathology; self-scale claims are stable across all loop orders to four decimal places; 4-loop is used for all reported numbers, Section~\ref{sec:loop-order}). The Model~A values should be read as within-reference-class, within-loop-order relative rankings rather than as calibrated significance levels. Within those conditions the qualitative ranking is stable. The $(c, b, t)$ at $\mu = m_\tau$ claim was formulated by the present author on the same FLAG/PDG cen