\section{Discussion}
\label{sec:discussion}

\subsection{What the analysis says about Koide-type quark relations}

Three observations follow.

First, no claim involving search across multiple triples combined with running has a low tail probability under either null model. The full-search $T \approx 0.5$ is not a marginal failure; it is fully consistent with noise under both audited tools, and the conclusion is stable across hierarchy-preserving variants of Model~A, the four correlation choices for Model~B, three alternative priors, and the rejection-sampling reframe of the perturbative-validity conditioning (Section~\ref{sec:loss-bias}). The qualitative ranking of claims is preserved across all alternative implementations.

Second, single-triple claims proposed in prior literature occupy a different position from the full search. The $(c,b,t)$ closure with $m_c$ evaluated at $\mu = m_\tau$ has a baseline Model~A tail probability of $\approx 0.003$ within the chosen reference class; under hierarchy-preserving variants of Model~A it has $\approx 0.004$--$0.007$ (Section~\ref{sec:hierarchy-null}). Its Model~B tail probability is $\approx 0.15$, which restates that its observed residual is $\approx 0.09\sigma_Q$ and carries no independent evidential content beyond that ratio. The Monte Carlo binomial standard error on the small Model~A values at $N \approx 67{,}000$ is of order $10^{-4}$, but this is not the dominant uncertainty: the prior-class sub-systematic (Section~\ref{sec:prior-sensitivity}) and the loop-order systematic (Section~\ref{sec:loop-order}) each individually exceed it, and the choice of reference class itself sets a wider scope-of-applicability bound (Section~\ref{sec:model-a}). The absolute Model~A values should therefore be read as within-condition relative rankings, not as calibrated tail probabilities; quoting them to more than two significant figures would overstate their meaning.

One feature of this particular claim warrants explicit statement rather than inference from the reference list. The $(c,b,t)$ at $\mu = m_\tau$ hypothesis was published by the present author~\citep{Brilliant2026cbt}, and the analysis reported here began as a sanity check on that prior claim before being extended to the full quark-side search space so that the same criteria could be applied uniformly to proposals by Rivero~\citep{Rivero2011}, Rodejohann and Zhang~\citep{RZ2011}, and Cao~\citep{Cao2012}. The claim is therefore pre-specified relative to the present audit, but it is not pre-registered against future data: it was formulated on the same FLAG/PDG central values the audit uses, and the prior publication is by the present author rather than by a third party. The reported $T = 0.002$ is a multiplicity-corrected characterization of that prior claim under the present audited search space and the chosen log-uniform prior; it is not an independent confirmation.

The discovery context of the $(c,b,t)$ at $\mu = m_\tau$ claim is worth noting because it bears on how the claim should be read alongside Rivero's earlier $(c,b,t)$ proposal. Rivero's $(c,b,t)$ entry is a self-scale (pole-mass) construction with residual at the $10^{-3}$ level on current FLAG/PDG values---two orders of magnitude looser than the $(c,b,t)$ at $\mu = m_\tau$ closure. The two should be regarded as distinct claims about the same triple, differing in evaluation-scale choice; the present author's contribution to the $(c,b,t)$ triple is the choice $\mu = m_\tau$, identified while studying a separate geometric construction (Descartes/Soddy-type stability properties of the Koide-saturating lepton triple, examined in~\citep{Brilliant2026strange}) rather than via exhaustive scan over scale candidates. This discovery context does not eliminate the post-hoc nature of the claim---no theoretical motivation can do so, since the FLAG/PDG values were known when the motivation was formulated---but it does mean the claim was not the output of an unconstrained search.

\paragraph{This paper as the registration step.} A claim formulated post-hoc on existing data is, by construction, untestable as an inferential statement on that same data; this is true of the $(c,b,t)$ at $\mu = m_\tau$ claim and of every other post-hoc claim in any field, including the historical Rivero, Cao, and Rodejohann-Zhang proposals. The standard remedy is a forward-looking test on independent data~\citep{CousinsLectures}: the post-hoc claim is frozen as a pre-registered hypothesis with quantitative drift thresholds, and subsequent data either causes the residual to converge or to drift outside those thresholds. Sections~\ref{sec:temporal} and especially Table~\ref{tab:drift} provide that registration: each surveyed claim is assigned a residual value and explicit drift thresholds against future $m_c$, $m_b$, $m_t$, $m_s$ revisions. The present audit therefore plays the role of the registration step in this paradigm, not of the forward-looking confirmation step. The latter is the work of subsequent FLAG/PDG releases over the next decade, on which the rankings reported here are conditional and to which they are exposed for falsification.

Third, Table~\ref{tab:phase1} and the matched-complexity knob-isolation test of Section~\ref{sec:isolation} together indicate that admitting non-self-scale running shifts the Model~A null distribution of best residuals toward smaller values by more than trial-count multiplicity alone accounts for (Figure~\ref{fig:knob_matched_N}). At matched subsample size $N' = 80$, running-only draws yield a median tail probability of $0.61$ while signs-only yields $0.38$, indicating that non-self-scale running is a distinct contributor to the noise floor of this search and not merely a vehicle for more trials. The observed closure at full freedom is typical under the full-freedom null ($T \approx 0.50$); this does not establish that non-self-scale running is illegitimate as a physical operation, only that searches admitting it need to be compared against null distributions that also admit it.

\subsection{Falsifiability of the surviving single-triple claim}

A statistical test against null models speaks to present-day significance. A separate question is whether a claim with a low tail probability under one null model is stable to anticipated improvements in mass measurements.

The $(c,b,t)$ closure with $m_c$ at $\mu = m_\tau$ has residual $|Q - 2/3| = 5.1 \times 10^{-5}$, currently $0.09\sigma_Q$. The dominant uncertainty contribution is $m_t$ ($\sim 86\%$ of variance). Even at projected FCC-ee precision ($\sigma_{m_t} \approx 0.05$~GeV, a $14\times$ improvement), the residual-to-uncertainty ratio reaches only $\sim 0.2\sigma$, so the closure is unlikely to become testable for exactness within foreseeable experimental precision. It would be falsified if the $m_t$ central value drifts by more than $\sim 0.5$~GeV ($0.7\sigma$ of current uncertainty), or if $m_c(m_c)$ or $m_b(m_b)$ shift by comparable fractions of their uncertainties.

\begin{table}[h]
\centering
\begin{tabular}{llcc}
\toprule
Claim & Key input & Breaks if drift $>$ & Testable when $\sigma <$ \\
\midrule
$(c,b,t)$ at $m_\tau$ & $m_t$ & $0.7\sigma$ ($0.5$~GeV) & not before FCC-ee \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\caption{Drift threshold for the surviving author-pre-specified single-triple claim (see Section~\ref{sec:discussion}).}
\label{tab:drift}
\end{table}

\subsection{Temporal convergence as an additional discriminator}
\label{sec:temporal}

Statistical tests against null models and central-value drift thresholds both speak to present-day significance. A third discriminator, available without any new theory, is whether the residual $|Q - 2/3|$ converges toward zero as measurement precision improves over time. A relation that is exact in nature should produce a residual that shrinks as the propagated $\sigma_Q$ shrinks; a relation that is a coincidence at a particular epoch should produce a residual that remains pinned at its accidental value while $\sigma_Q$ decreases past it.

The original lepton Koide relation is the textbook example. When Koide proposed $Q = 2/3$ in 1981--1983, the world-average $m_\tau$ was $1784.2 \pm 3.2$~MeV, while the value required by the formula given $m_e$ and $m_\mu$ was $1776.97$~MeV. BES measurements published in 1992 and 1996 converged to $1776.96 \pm 0.31$~MeV, and subsequent refinements have remained within $\sim 1\sigma$ of the same value (PDG~2024: $1776.86 \pm 0.12$~MeV). The residual $|Q - 2/3|$ has tracked the shrinking $m_\tau$ uncertainty downward across four decades.

By contrast, the Rivero and Cao quark-side claims with low Model~A tail probabilities do not show the same pattern. The Rivero $(s, c, b)$ residual at self-scales has remained in the range $|Q - 2/3| \approx 7.5$--$8.2 \times 10^{-3}$ since the FLAG~2013 update introduced $N_f = 2 + 1 + 1$ averages: across FLAG~2013, 2016, 2019, 2021, and~2024 the residual has not budged outside that band while the propagated $\sigma_Q$ has shrunk by roughly a factor of three to its present value of $\sim 5.4 \times 10^{-4}$. The Cao $(c, b, t)$ self-scale residual has shown a similar stability, sitting near $3.5$--$4.7 \times 10^{-3}$ across the same period (slightly increasing as $m_t$ has been refined). In both cases, the ratio of the residual to the propagated $\sigma_Q$ is currently of order $9$--$14$.

\begin{table}[h]
\centering
\small
\begin{tabular}{lcccc}
\toprule
Claim & 2013 $|Q - 2/3|$ & 2024 $|Q - 2/3|$ & 2024 in $\sigma_Q$ & Trend \\
\midrule
Lepton Koide                          & $\sim 10^{-5}$       & $6 \times 10^{-6}$   & $1.0\sigma$  & converging since 1981 \\
Rivero $(s, c, b)$ self [signed]      & $8.2 \times 10^{-3}$ & $7.5 \times 10^{-3}$ & $13.9\sigma$ & stable; non-convergent \\
Cao $(c, b, t)$ self                  & $3.5 \times 10^{-3}$ & $4.7 \times 10^{-3}$ & $8.6\sigma$  & stable / slow drift \\
$(c, b, t)$ at $\mu = m_\tau$         & ---                  & $5.1 \times 10^{-5}$ & $0.09\sigma$ & not yet assessable \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\caption{Temporal stability of $|Q - 2/3|$ for the four most-discussed Koide-type claims. Lepton Koide is the only one whose residual has tracked decreasing $\sigma_Q$ downward. Rivero and Cao have residuals an order of magnitude or more larger than current $\sigma_Q$ that have not converged with measurement improvements. The $(c, b, t)$ at $\mu = m_\tau$ claim was first identified post-hoc on current FLAG/PDG central values~\citep{Brilliant2026cbt}, so its present small residual carries no temporal information; meaningful assessment requires future independent measurement updates.}
\label{tab:temporal-summary}
\end{table}

The $(c, b, t)$ at $\mu = m_\tau$ claim cannot yet be assessed by this criterion. It was identified post-hoc on the current FLAG/PDG central values~\citep{Brilliant2026cbt}, so its present small residual reflects the conditions under which it was selected and contains no information about whether the relation is exact. As $m_c$, $m_b$, and (to a smaller extent) $m_t$ are refined in subsequent FLAG and PDG releases, the residual will either converge toward zero (consistent with an exact relation) or drift away (consistent with selection on a particular set of central values). The drift thresholds in Table~\ref{tab:drift} provide a quantitative version of the same statement.


\subsection{A geometric extension treated separately}

A second class of Koide-type claim involves geometric constructions on the lepton triple rather than algebraic relations among quark masses. One such construction---the squared outer Soddy curvature of the Koide-saturating lepton triple, evaluated at the scale $\Sigma m_\ell$, compared against $m_s$---has been examined in a separate preprint~\citep{Brilliant2026strange}. The present note's framework does not directly transfer: that construction is a closed-form prediction of one output ($m_s$) from a specific geometric invariant of the lepton triple, not a search over a space of (triple, sign, scale) combinations, so the LEE machinery developed here does not apply in the same way. The Model~A random-spectrum null is also not the appropriate reference class for a single geometric prediction. The analogous concerns for that construction---multiplicity over choice of geometric invariant, choice of evaluation scale, and the data-dependent hypothesis-formation issue if the construction was identified on the current $m_s$ value---require their own treatment, and the temporal-trajectory test of Section~\ref{sec:temporal} is the most directly transferable element. We defer that analysis to follow-up work.

\subsection{Limitations}

The search space is finite, discrete, and physically interpretable; it does not exhaust all conceivable Koide-type formulations. A continuous scale scan would inflate the trial count and the implied LEE penalty without bound, so the present discrete audit should be read as a lower-complexity benchmark, not an exhaustive accounting. We do not vary the algebraic target ($Q = 2/3$ throughout), the mass scheme ($\overline{\text{MS}}$ only), or the fermion content (no neutrinos, no boson masses).

The Model~A prior is conditional on perturbative validity, implemented by rejection sampling (Section~\ref{sec:loss-bias}); this is an explicit feature of the chosen reference class and is verified to be implementation-independent within CRunDec. Reported tail probabilities are therefore conditional on the perturbatively-valid log-uniform reference class, which is one of several defensible choices.

The 1/3/4/5-loop convergence study (Section~\ref{sec:loop-order}) shows the absolute Model~A tail probabilities for \emph{running} claims to vary by $\approx 0.05$--$0.13$ across well-converged loop orders; \emph{self-scale} claims (Cao, Rivero, chain-no-run, 20-triple self) are perfectly stable across all loop orders. The 2-loop run is excluded from this assessment because the observed Koide closure has not perturbatively converged at that order ($|Q - 2/3|$ is an order of magnitude larger than at higher orders), making the 2-loop full-search comparison internally consistent at 2-loop but not informative for the converged Koide quantity. All reported Model~A numbers use 4-loop running.

Sensitivity of the two null models is examined in Section~\ref{sec:robustness}, where the running implementation, the random-spectrum prior family, the assumption of uncorrelated FLAG/PDG uncertainties, and the rejection-sampling reframe are each tested.


\section{Conclusion}
\label{sec:conclusion}

Under the two tools audited here, at full search freedom the observed closures reproduce the median null residual, yielding tail probability $\approx 0.50$ under the 4-loop Model~A random-spectrum null and $\approx 0.50$ under the Model~B measurement-noise bootstrap. A matched-complexity knob-isolation test (Section~\ref{sec:isolation}, Figure~\ref{fig:knob_matched_N}) indicates that admitting non-self-scale running is a distinct contributor to the Model~A noise floor beyond what trial-count multiplicity alone produces. Sensitivity checks (Section~\ref{sec:robustness}) indicate that the full-search qualitative result is stable under the running implementation, under the choice of prior family within the tested range, under plausible correlation structure in the FLAG/PDG uncertainties, and under the rejection-sampling reframe of the perturbative-validity conditioning. The absolute Model~A tail probabilities for running claims carry a loop-order spread of $\approx 0.05$--$0.13$ across orders 1, 3, 4, 5 and reach $\approx 0.5$ when 2-loop is included (Section~\ref{sec:loop-order}; the 2-loop full-search value of $\approx 0.04$ is explained by perturbative non-convergence of the observed Koide combination at 2-loop). Across all five loop orders the qualitative ranking is preserved.

Pre-specified single-triple claims occupy an intermediate position. The $(c,b,t)$ closure at $\mu = m_\tau$ has a baseline Model~A tail probability of $\approx 0.003$, $\approx 0.004$--$0.007$ under hierarchy-preserving variants, and a Model~B tail probability of $\approx 0.15$ that restates its observed residual ratio $|r|/\sigma_Q \approx 0.09$. The claim was published by the present author in~\citep{Brilliant2026cbt} prior to the present audit, and the audit began as a sanity check on that claim before being extended to the full quark-side search space; the present analysis therefore provides a multiplicity-corrected restatement of a prior author claim under the chosen log-uniform prior class and 4-loop running, not an independent confirmation. The temporal trajectory of its residual across future FLAG/PDG releases (Section~\ref{sec:temporal}, Table~\ref{tab:drift}) is what a subsequent forward-looking evaluation would draw on.

The analysis, all code, all seeds, and the audited trial list are in the repository~\citep{RepoMC}.


\section*{Computational note}

All computations are reproducible from~\citep{RepoMC}. Search space: \texttt{search\_space.json} ($12{,}960$ trials, audited in \texttt{trial\_list\_complete.csv}). Running: four-loop $\overline{\text{MS}}$ via \texttt{CRunDec}~\citep{CRunDec}, with thresholds computed from the input mass spectrum (SM values for Models~A and~B baseline; perturbed values for bootstrap variants; random values for random-spectrum draws). Inputs: FLAG~2024, PDG~2024.

Random-spectrum MC (Model~A): $100{,}000$ retained experiments in the main run (rejection-sampling acceptance rate $\approx 67\%$ from the unconditioned log-uniform prior; an earlier $10{,}000$-experiment run gave values agreeing within $1$--$2$ SE), full CRunDec on every retained draw. Bootstrap MC (Model~B): $2{,}000$ experiments per correlation variant, full CRunDec on every draw, with perturbations applied uniformly to all claims including self-scale-only claims (an earlier draft implementation evaluated self-scale claims at unperturbed central values; this has been corrected). Surrogate validation: $500$ paired draws comparing surrogate to full CRunDec (the surrogate failed validation and was not used in the final analysis). Hierarchy-preserving null: $10{,}000$ experiments per variant. Matched-complexity knob-isolation test: $K = 1000$ random subsamples of size $N' \in \{40, 80, 160, 320, 640, 1280, 2560, 3240\}$ drawn from each of the signs-only ($80$), running-only ($3{,}240$), and full-search ($12{,}960$) trial pools. Loop-order convergence study: $N = 10{,}000$ paired draws at 1-, 2-, 3-, 4-, and 5-loop CRunDec (the 2-loop run is excluded from the convergence assessment because the observed Koide closure has not converged at 2-loop, an effect on the observed value rather than the null; documented in Section~\ref{sec:loop-order}). Analytic 1-loop crosscheck: pure-Python closed-form $\alpha_s(\mu)$ with simplified threshold matching, $N = 10{,}000$ paired draws (rejection rate $13.4\%$ vs.\ $32.7\%$ for full CRunDec, reflecting differing perturbative-validity regions). Rejection-sampling reframe consistency check: explicit rejection sampling implementation drawing $14{,}783$ unconditioned attempts to obtain $10{,}000$ retained valid spectra; resulting tail probabilities agree with the original implementation within MC noise. Distributional comparison of rejected vs.\ retained subsamples: $3{,}269$ rejected vs.\ $6{,}731$ retained under surrogate running. All seeds documented in the repository.


