\subsection{Rejection sampling and the conditional prior}
\label{sec:loss-bias}

The Model~A prior is conditional on perturbative validity, implemented by rejection sampling (Section~\ref{sec:model-a}). Approximately $33\%$ of unconditioned log-uniform draws are rejected because the resulting spectra produce pathological QCD configurations (charm-bottom thresholds too close, $\alpha_s$ blow-up, etc.) for which the running prescription is ill-posed. We verify that the conditioning is well-behaved by two diagnostics on the implementation, and note one earlier diagnostic that we no longer rely on.

\paragraph{Rejection-sampling reframe consistency check.} We re-implemented Model~A as explicit rejection sampling: continue drawing from the unconditioned log-uniform prior until $N = 10{,}000$ retained valid spectra are obtained (acceptance rate $\approx 67.6\%$). The resulting tail fractions agree with the conditional-prior implementation within MC noise: the maximum absolute difference across the nine claims is $0.020$ (driven by MC noise at a different random seed), with the running claims agreeing to within $0.01$ and the full-search tail fraction agreeing to within $0.002$. The two implementations are mathematically equivalent and the conditional-prior framing is therefore not implementation-sensitive.

\paragraph{Engine-switching crosscheck and engine-dependence of the conditional prior.} We re-ran Model~A using 2-loop CRunDec in place of 4-loop, on paired draws ($N = 10{,}000$). The rejected set is identical: the same $3{,}269$ draws are rejected at both loop orders, confirming that within CRunDec the perturbative-validity region does not depend on loop order. We additionally re-ran Model~A using a pure-Python analytic 1-loop running scheme (closed-form $\alpha_s(\mu)$ with simplified threshold matching). This scheme has substantially lower rejection rate ($13.4\%$) because its simpler matching tolerates configurations that full CRunDec cannot handle. The two engines therefore implement \emph{different conditional priors}: ``perturbatively valid spectra under full CRunDec'' is a strictly smaller set than ``perturbatively valid spectra under analytic 1-loop running.'' This is an intrinsic feature of the conditioning, not a numerical artifact: the boundary of the perturbatively-valid region depends on which running prescription is used to define ``valid.'' Under the analytic 1-loop scheme the full-search tail fraction is $\approx 0.37$, versus $\approx 0.50$ under 4-loop CRunDec. The difference is a combination of two effects---a shift in the conditional prior (different perturbative-validity regions) and a loop-order shift in the observed Koide value (Section~\ref{sec:loop-order})---and we cannot cleanly separate them. The qualitative result (full-search closure not extreme) holds under both engines; the precise tail fraction depends on the choice of engine, and we report 4-loop CRunDec values throughout.

\paragraph{Diagnostic not used.} An earlier draft compared the distribution of best residuals between rejected and retained draws using the surrogate running scheme to assess whether the rejection set was biased. We do not rely on that diagnostic in the current analysis because the surrogate did not reproduce full-CRunDec results at the per-draw level (Section~\ref{sec:surrogate-validation}), so a comparison routed through the surrogate is not informative about the conditional prior implemented with full CRunDec. The two diagnostics above use exact full-CRunDec computations on the rejection-sampled prior and are not subject to that concern.

\paragraph{Summary.} The Model~A reported tail fractions are conditional on the perturbatively-valid log-uniform prior, implemented by rejection. The conditioning is an explicit feature of the reference class, not a missing-data problem. Within CRunDec the conditioning is loop-order-independent (same draws are rejected at every CRunDec loop order); across running engines the conditioning is engine-dependent (the analytic 1-loop scheme accepts a strictly larger set of spectra), and we report 4-loop CRunDec values throughout. The engine-dependent component of the conditioning contributes to the absolute-value uncertainty but does not change the qualitative ranking of claims.



\subsection{Loop-order convergence of the observed Koide combination}
\label{sec:loop-order}

To assess the sensitivity of Model~A tail probabilities to the perturbative order of the running implementation, we re-ran Model~A at 1-loop, 2-loop, 3-loop, 4-loop, and 5-loop CRunDec on identical paired draws ($N = 10{,}000$). For \emph{self-scale} claims (those evaluated at $\mu = m_i$ without inter-flavor running, including Cao $(c,b,t)$, Rivero $(s,c,b)$, and the chain-no-run and 20-triple self families), the tail probabilities are stable to four decimal places across all loop orders, as expected: these claims do not invoke running across flavor thresholds and the loop-order choice does not change their numerical evaluation.

For \emph{running} claims, the picture is more subtle and the loop-order systematic is the largest among the loop-order tested. The full-search tail fraction returns $\{0.57, 0.04, 0.63, 0.50, 0.53\}$ at $\{1, 2, 3, 4, 5\}$ loops respectively. Excluding the 2-loop point, the values cluster within a spread of $\approx 0.05$--$0.13$ across the other four orders, with 4-loop and 5-loop closest to each other (consistent with perturbative convergence at higher orders). The 2-loop point is anomalous and has a clean physical explanation: at 2-loop, the SM-mass observed Koide combination itself has not perturbatively converged. The 2-loop observed value is $m_c(m_\tau) = 1.159$~GeV with $|Q - 2/3| = 5.1 \times 10^{-4}$, versus $m_c(m_\tau) = 1.143$~GeV with $|Q - 2/3| = 5.1 \times 10^{-5}$ at 4-loop---the 2-loop observed Koide residual is an order of magnitude larger. This worse observed value is more easily beaten by random-spectrum draws in the matched 2-loop null, yielding a small tail fraction that is internally consistent at 2-loop but reflects that the Koide closure is itself a higher-loop phenomenon. The 2-loop observed-value non-convergence is a property of the underlying physics, not of the search.

To avoid any post-hoc selection on which loop orders to report, we list the full-loop-order spread for all claims and let the reader decide how to weight the 2-loop value. For the full search, the absolute Model~A tail fraction lies in $[0.04, 0.63]$ across orders $\{1, 2, 3, 4, 5\}$, with the lower end driven entirely by the 2-loop observed-value non-convergence. For the $(c,b,t)$ at $\mu = m_\tau$ claim, the spread across the same five orders is $\{0.003, 0.007, 0.005, 0.002, 0.004\}$---a maximum value of $0.007$, well below $0.01$ at every loop order including 2-loop. For the $(c,b,t)$ all-signs-with-running family, the spread is $\{0.010, 0.018, 0.013, 0.007, 0.013\}$, with all values below $0.02$. Across all running claims and across all five loop orders, the qualitative ordering is preserved.

The headline qualitative result---that the full-search closure is not extreme under any audited tool---survives every loop order including 2-loop ($T = 0.04$ at 2-loop is below the conventional $0.05$ threshold but well above any reasonable significance bar for a $12{,}960$-trial search; the higher-loop values are firmly non-significant by any framework). All Model~A numbers reported in the main text and Table~\ref{tab:pvalues} use 4-loop running, which is the conventional standard for $\overline{\text{MS}}$ quark mass running.



