\section{Discussion}
\label{sec:discussion}

\subsection{What the analysis says about Koide-type quark relations}

Three observations follow.

First, no claim involving search across multiple triples combined with running has a low tail probability under either null model. The full-search $T \approx 0.5$ is not a marginal failure; it is fully consistent with noise under both audited tools, and the conclusion is stable across hierarchy-preserving variants of Model~A, the four correlation choices for Model~B, three alternative priors, and the rejection-sampling reframe of the perturbative-validity conditioning (Section~\ref{sec:loss-bias}). The qualitative ranking of claims is preserved across all alternative implementations.

Second, single-triple claims proposed in prior literature occupy a different position from the full search. The $(c,b,t)$ closure with $m_c$ evaluated at $\mu = m_\tau$ has a baseline Model~A tail probability of $\approx 0.003$ within the chosen reference class; under hierarchy-preserving variants of Model~A it has $\approx 0.004$--$0.007$ (Section~\ref{sec:hierarchy-null}). Its Model~B tail probability is $\approx 0.15$, which restates that its observed residual is $\approx 0.09\sigma_Q$ and carries no independent evidential content beyond that ratio. The Monte Carlo binomial standard error on the small Model~A values at $N \approx 67{,}000$ is of order $10^{-4}$, but this is not the dominant uncertainty: the prior-class sub-systematic (Section~\ref{sec:prior-sensitivity}) and the loop-order systematic (Section~\ref{sec:loop-order}) each individually exceed it, and the choice of reference class itself sets a wider scope-of-applicability bound (Section~\ref{sec:model-a}). The absolute Model~A values should therefore be read as within-condition relative rankings, not as calibrated tail probabilities; quoting them to more than two significant figures would overstate their meaning.

One feature of this particular claim warrants explicit statement rather than inference from the reference list. The $(c,b,t)$ at $\mu = m_\tau$ hypothesis was published by the present author~\citep{Brilliant2026cbt}, and the analysis reported here began as a sanity check on that prior claim before being extended to the full quark-side search space so that the same criteria could be applied uniformly to proposals by Rivero~\citep{Rivero2011}, Rodejohann and Zhang~\citep{RZ2011}, and Cao~\citep{Cao2012}. The claim is therefore pre-specified relative to the present audit, but it is not pre-registered against future data: it was formulated on the same FLAG/PDG central values the audit uses, and the prior publication is by the present author rather than by a third party. The reported $T = 0.002$ is a multiplicity-corrected characterization of that prior claim under the present audited search space and the chosen log-uniform prior; it is not an independent confirmation.

The discovery context of the $(c,b,t)$ at $\mu = m_\tau$ claim is worth noting because it bears on how the claim should be read alongside Rivero's earlier $(c,b,t)$ proposal. Rivero's $(c,b,t)$ entry is a self-scale (pole-mass) construction with residual at the $10^{-3}$ level on current FLAG/PDG values---two orders of magnitude looser than the $(c,b,t)$ at $\mu = m_\tau$ closure. The two should be regarded as distinct claims about the same triple, differing in evaluation-scale choice; the present author's contribution to the $(c,b,t)$ triple is the choice $\mu = m_\tau$, identified while studying a separate geometric construction (Descartes/Soddy-type stability properties of the Koide-saturating lepton triple, examined in~\citep{Brilliant2026strange}) rather than via exhaustive scan over scale candidates. This discovery context does not eliminate the post-hoc nature of the claim---no theoretical motivation can do so, since the FLAG/PDG values were known when the motivation was formulated---but it does mean the claim was not the output of an unconstrained search.

\paragraph{This paper as the registration step.} A claim formulated post-hoc on existing data is, by construction, untestable as an inferential statement on that same data; this is true of the $(c,b,t)$ at $\mu = m_\tau$ claim and of every other post-hoc claim in any field, including the historical Rivero, Cao, and Rodejohann-Zhang proposals. The standard remedy is a forward-looking test on independent data~\citep{CousinsLectures}: the post-hoc claim is frozen as a pre-registered hypothesis with quantitative drift thresholds, and subsequent data either causes the residual to converge or to drift outside those thresholds. Sections~\ref{sec:temporal} and especially Table~\ref{tab:drift} provide that registration: each surveyed claim is assigned a residual value and explicit drift thresholds against future $m_c$, $m_b$, $m_t$, $m_s$ revisions. The present audit therefore plays the role of the registration step in this paradigm, not of the forward-looking confirmation step. The latter is the work of subsequent FLAG/PDG releases over the next decade, on which the rankings reported here are conditional and to which they are exposed for falsification.

Third, Table~\ref{tab:phase1} and the matched-complexity knob-isolation test of Section~\ref{sec:isolation} together indicate that admitting non-self-scale running shifts the Model~A null distribution of best residuals toward smaller values by more than trial-count multiplicity alone accounts for (Figure~\ref{fig:knob_matched_N}). At matched subsample size $N' = 80$, running-only draws yield a median tail probability of $0.61$ while signs-only yields $0.38$, indicating that non-self-scale running is a distinct contributor to the noise floor of this search and not merely a vehicle for more trials. The observed closure at full freedom is typical under the full-freedom null ($T \approx 0.50$); this does not establish that non-self-scale running is illegitimate as a physical operation, only that searches admitting it need to be compared against null distributions that also admit it.

\subsection{Falsifiability of the surviving single-triple claim}

A statistical test against null models speaks to present-day significance. A separate question is whether a claim with a low tail probability under one null model is stable to anticipated improvements in mass measurements.

The $(c,b,t)$ closure with $m_c$ at $\mu = m_\tau$ has residual $|Q - 2/3| = 5.1 \times 10^{-5}$, currently $0.09\sigma_Q$. The dominant uncertainty contribution is $m_t$ ($\sim 86\%$ of variance). Even at projected FCC-ee precision ($\sigma_{m_t} \approx 0.05$~GeV, a $14\times$ improvement), the residual-to-uncertainty ratio reaches only $\sim 0.2\sigma$, so the closure is unlikely to become testable for exactness within foreseeable experimental precision. It would be falsified if the $m_t$ central value drifts by more than $\sim 0.5$~GeV ($0.7\sigma$ of current uncertainty), or if $m_c(m_c)$ or $m_b(m_b)$ shift by comparable fractions of their uncertainties.

